## Bandit Level 12 → Level 13

**Challenge:** The password for the next level is stored in the file data.txt, which is a hexdump of a file that has been repeatedly compressed. For this level it may be useful to create a directory under /tmp in which you can work. Use mkdir with a hard to guess directory name. Or better, use the command “mktemp -d”. Then copy the datafile using cp, and rename it using mv (read the manpages!)

**Solution:**
```bash
xxd -r hexdump_data compressed_data
mv compressed_data compressed_data.gz
gzip -d compressed_data.gz
mv compressed_data compressed_data.bz2
bzip2 -d compressed_data.bz2
mv compressed_data compressed_data.tar
tar -xf compressed_data.tar

```

**Explanation:** 
`xxd -r hexdump_data compressed_data` this command reverts from hexdump to normal file.
`xxd` this command will be used repeated after any changes to the file. this will allow it to be in human readble form and let use see if the file hase been compressed using gzip, bzip2 or has been archived.

If the file has been compressed using gzip, "1f8b" will be the first line of the file when `xxd` command is used.
to decompress this file you must rename the file to end with ".gz" using this command:
`mv compressed_data compressed_data.gz`
Once the name has been changed run this command to decopress the data with this file:
`gzip -d compressed_data.gz`

If the file has been compressed using bzip2, "425A68" will be the first line of the file when `xxd` command is used.
to decompress this file you must rename the file to end with ".bz2" using this command:
`mv compressed_data compressed_data.bz2`
Once the name has been changed run this command to decopress the data with this file:
`bzip2 -d compressed_data.bz2`

After multiple decompressions the file will eventually become a archive, which we must extract.
If along the first line after rnning `xxd` you see a file names "data5.bin" thismens we need to extract the archived file.
Using this comand you change the file name:
`mv compressed_data compressed_data.tar`
This command will be used to extract the archived file:
`tar -xf compressed_data.tar`
Once this command is used you will have a new file in your directory which has been extracted from the previous file.

You must keep using the xxd command to see what file type you are at and apply the commands listed bove. eventualy after multiple decompressions and extractions you will be able to read the password for the next level.



**What I learned:** You can view a binary file in a human readable formart using hexdump.
**Password:** FO5dwFsc0cbaIiH0h8J2eUks2vdTDwAn

